<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
  <head>
    <link rel="preconnect" href="https://fonts.googleapis.com" />
    <link rel="preconnect" href="https://fonts.gstatic.com" crossorigin />
    <link
      href="https://fonts.googleapis.com/css2?family=EB+Garamond:ital,wght@0,400..800;1,400..800&family=IBM+Plex+Sans:ital,wght@0,100..700;1,100..700&display=swap"
      rel="stylesheet"
    />
    <meta charset="utf-8" />
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1" />
    <meta name="csrf-token" content={get_csrf_token()} />
    <.live_title default="" suffix="  - Jamie Curle">
      {assigns[:page_title]}
    </.live_title>
    <link phx-track-static rel="stylesheet" href={~p"/assets/css/app.css"} />
    <script defer phx-track-static type="text/javascript" src={~p"/assets/js/app.js"}>
    </script>
    <script>
      (() => {
        const setTheme = (theme) => {
          if (theme === "system") {
            localStorage.removeItem("phx:theme");
            document.documentElement.removeAttribute("data-theme");
          } else {
            localStorage.setItem("phx:theme", theme);
            document.documentElement.setAttribute("data-theme", theme);
          }
        };
        if (!document.documentElement.hasAttribute("data-theme")) {
          setTheme(localStorage.getItem("phx:theme") || "system");
        }
        window.addEventListener("storage", (e) => e.key === "phx:theme" && setTheme(e.newValue || "system"));
        
        window.addEventListener("phx:set-theme", (e) => setTheme(e.target.dataset.phxTheme));
      })();
    </script>
  </head>
  <body
    class={["h-full flex flex-col", assigns[:body_class]]}
    id={assigns[:body_id] || ""}
  >
    <ul class="menu menu-horizontal w-full relative z-10 flex items-center gap-4 px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8 justify-end">
      <%= if @current_scope do %>
        <li>
          {@current_scope.user.email}
        </li>
        <li>
          <.link href={~p"/users/log-out"} method="delete">Log out</.link>
        </li>
      <% end %>
    </ul>
    <div class="layout">
      <header class="navbar px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8"></header>

      <main>
        {@inner_content}
      </main>

      <footer class="border-t border-base-content/10 bg-base-200 pt-8 pb-8 md:min-h-screen">
        <div class="p-16 about flex flex-col sm:flex-row border-b border-base-content/10 bg-base-200 pt-8 pb-8 ">
          <div class="text w-full sm:w-2/3 text-sm p-8">
            <h1>Hello, I'm Jamie Curle &hellip;</h1>

            <p>
              I started out in technology in 1998 as a web designer. Design forms the basis for
              my undergrad and postgrad qualifications. Design is deeper that appearance or shape,
              it's a process and a mindset that creates novel solutions of value to problems. It's
              simply software engineering expressed in abstract terms.
            </p>
            <p>
              I'm an outside-in software engineer, that means user experience first, operational
              efficiency second at a 51/49% ratio. Function first, form second. My professional
              engineering practice is informed by a solid grounding in infosec, privacy, teaching and of course:
              design.
            </p>
            <p>
              AI is a force multiplier and I embrace it. Sometimes it writes the code,
              sometime it writes the tests. It nearly always does the first few drafts of any plans. But there's a danger
              in AI usage in that over-reliance turns into cognitive atrophy. That's why it's more important than ever
              to invest in yourself.  Average multiplied by a factor of ten will always be less powerful than
              exceptional multiplied by the same factor. That's why I constantly invest in myself.
            </p>
            <p>
              Leadership has always found me. The patterns had always been there the earliest example was when I was ten years old.
              I was in third year junior school and I was made captain of the forth year team. I wasn't the best player, but I was
              the one who cemented the team together. In nearly every situation I've found myself in professionally, I'ved ended
              up leading. I don't seek it, it seeks me. If you're reading this becasue I could be working with you and you're afriad
              I'm going to steal the leadership thunder then stop worrying. I'm just as good at following as I am leading and that's
              becasue I understand the challenges you face as leader. I aim to help you solve them at best and at least make them easier.
            </p>
            <p>
              I can lead and I can be led. Both are an active persuit requiring meaningful
              communication and intentional action. To me, leading is clearing the blocks and setting
              the scene for your team members success on short, near and long term basis.
            </p>
            <p>
              Hierarchy is a useful part of leadership becasue it brings operational efficiencies. But when leadership
              starts being cut and diluted with dominance, cult thinking or control it ceases being an aspect of leadership and
              often starts being a weird mirror into the broken soul the of leader. I've been situations like that. I left
              becasue I don't tolerate it and I certainly don't feed it by giving it attention.
            </p>
            <p>
              Very early on in my life I was fortunate to have exposure to exceptional teachers.
              They've impacted my life deeply and put me on a lifelong journey to be a well rounded
              human being. Mrs Dearden, Mr Gomersaul, Mr Nicololson, Mr Mitchinson and Doug Veitch
              & Jean Stoker: thank you.
            </p>
            <p>
              On that journey to be a well rounded human being, I've spent time as a drummer, olympic weightlifter,
              arborist, teacher and an avid cook / bread baker. I always come back to software, the internet and building.
            </p>
            <p>
              I've been formally meditating on and off for a decade. It's insightful on
              an existential level and very useful in managing distraction and especially
              useful in cultivating attention. I don't judge myself for not being consistent.
              Were you aware of your breathing or your posture before I pointed it out?
            </p>
            <p>
              Whilst I may use AI to gather my thoughts, I <strong>do not</strong>
              use AI to express them here. The right hemisphere is humanity's greatest asset.
              AI doesn't have a right hemisphere, only a synthetic left one. And this site is about me and only I can
              write that.
            </p>
            <p>
              Finally, it's all about joy. Not fleeting hedonistic joy and not joy at the expense of others. The joy that I seek
              to harvest in my work and personal life is the kind creates smiles and connects people in real life through
              cyberspace or meatspace.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div class="photo w-full sm:w-1/3">
            <p class="mb-4">
              <img
                src="/images/jc_dark.jpg"
                alt="An impromptu photograph of Jamie Curle from 2025 that somehow turned into his main profile picture."
                width="300px"
                class="hidden [[data-theme=dark]_&]:block rounded-[300px]"
              />
              <img
                src="/images/jc_light.jpg"
                alt="An impromptu photograph of Jamie Curle from 2025 that somehow turned into his main profile picture, but with a AI tweaked background colour."
                width="300px"
                class="block [[data-theme=dark]_&]:hidden rounded-[300px]"
              />
            </p>

            <.theme_toggle />
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="smallprint p-8">
          <p class="text-xs text-base-content/70 uppercase">
            &copy; {Date.utc_today().year} Jamie Curle.
          </p>
        </div>
      </footer>
    </div>
  </body>
</html>
